These are related (thinkers are members of Romans) but not identical: one is a specific subgroup (intellectuals/philosophers/thinkers) while the other is the general population/society. Therefore they should not be merged.

These are distinct collectives: one denotes intellectuals/thinkers from Rome (people concerned with ideas), the other denotes rulers (emperors) with political/military role. They are related but not identical.

Stoicism is a specific philosophical school (originating in Greece) that was adopted and practiced in Rome; Roman culture refers broadly to the social, artistic, religious and intellectual life of Rome. They are related (Stoicism influenced Roman thought) but are distinct kinds of entities — a philosophy vs a civilization's culture — so they should not be merged.

‘medieval Europe’ denotes Europe during the Middle Ages, a temporal subset of the broader geographical entity ‘Europe’. The two names refer to related but not identical entities: one is the continent in general, the other is the continent in a specific historical period. They should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different regional constructs: 'medieval Europe' denotes the post-Roman, medieval political/cultural region that inherited Roman legal codification, while the 'Roman Mediterranean' denotes the Mediterranean region organized and enabled by Roman institutions. They are related (the legacy of the Roman Mediterranean shaped medieval Europe) but are not the same geographic-political entity or timeframe, so they should not be merged.

Both mentions refer to the broad cultural/civilizational phenomenon of Rome — one called “Roman civilization” described by monuments/materiality, the other “Roman culture” described as Rome’s culture influenced by Greek background and Roman traditions. These are not distinct entities (e.g., different institutions or places) but two ways of naming the same cultural entity. They should be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct civilizations: one is Roman culture/civilization (the culture and institutions of ancient Rome) and the other is Greek civilization. They are related—Rome was shaped by Greek background and had contact with Greek civilization—but they are not the same entity and should not be merged.

The two entities are related but not identical. "Roman culture/civilization" refers broadly to the social, artistic, institutional, and material civilization of Rome across periods. "Roman sculpture" is a specific artistic category within Roman culture. One is a general cultural/civilizational entity, the other is a subset (a type of art) and thus should remain distinct.

Entity 1 describes the culture and civilization of ancient Rome (a cultural concept), while Entity 2 denotes the Romans as the people/social/political collective. These are closely related but distinct: one is a cultural/civilizational concept, the other is a population/political body. They are not strictly identical and should not be merged.

'Roman proletariat' refers specifically to the lower-class segment of the broader population of 'Romans'. 'Romans' denotes the entire people/social body of Rome, encompassing citizens of many classes including, later, proletarians. These are related but not identical: one is a subset/class within the other rather than the same entity.

The 'Roman proletariat' denotes a specific socio-economic subgroup (the lower-class, landless urban poor) within the broader collective 'Romans' (the entire people/citizenry of Rome). They are related but not identical: one is a subset (class) of the other. Thus they should not be merged.

Both names refer to the same social class in Rome: the proletarii (Latin) were the Roman proletariat — the lower-class citizens whose principal contribution to the state was child-bearing and who often lived in poor, crowded conditions. Descriptions match complementary aspects of the same group rather than distinct entities.

The proletarii are a specific social class within Roman society (the urban poor/lower class), while 'Romans' refers to the entire people and civic body of Rome. They are related (Romans could include proletarii, and some Roman citizens became proletarians) but are not the same singular entity; one is a subgroup of the other rather than identical.

The proletarii are a specific socio-economic class within Roman society (the urban poor/proletariat). "Romans" refers to the entire people/social order of Rome and the broader civic body; it includes many classes including the proletarii. They are related (proletarii are a subset of Romans) but not identical. Therefore they should not be merged.

The proletarii are a specific socioeconomic subgroup within the broader collective 'Romans'. They are not identical to the entire Roman people or Roman citizen body, but rather a subset (the urban poor). Their names and descriptions indicate different scope and referents (class vs. entire people), so they should not be merged.

These two refer to distinct social groups within Roman society: 'proletarii' denotes the lowest class/urban poor (the Roman proletariat), whereas 'Roman ruling élite' denotes the governing/upper class selected through Roman institutions. They are not the same entity—related but opposite ends of social hierarchy.

The proletarii (proletariat) and the plebs/plebeians both refer to common people in Roman society but denote different social groups and concepts. The plebs/plebeians were the broader class of common citizens with specific political identity and history (conflict of the orders, ability to check magistrates), while the proletarii specifically denote the poorest class within Roman citizens whose perceived value was producing offspring. They overlap (both are lower-status commoners) but are not strictly identical.

The two referents are different: 'Roman slave' denotes the class of enslaved people within Roman society, while 'Romans' denotes the Roman people/citizen body and society as a whole. They are related (slaves are part of Roman society) but not identical entities.

These two refer to distinct social groups in Roman society. "Roman slave" denotes enslaved persons who lacked citizenship and could sometimes earn freedom; "proletarii" denotes the lowest class of free Roman citizens (the urban poor) whose contribution was childbearing. They are related (both low in social hierarchy) but not identical.

The two entries refer to different groups: 'Romans' denotes the people/citizen body and social order of Rome, while 'Roman slave' denotes the class of enslaved individuals within Roman society. They are related (one is a subgroup defined by legal and social status) but not the same entity and should not be merged.

Entity 1 denotes the social category 'Roman slaves' (the enslaved population within Roman society). Entity 2 denotes 'Romans' broadly — the people/citizen body of Rome, including citizens and the social order. These are related but distinct: slaves are a subpopulation within Roman society with different legal status from 'Romans' (citizens). They are not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

Both refer to the same class of persons (slaves) but Entity 1 specifies the Roman context; Entity 2 is a generic description of slaves. They are not strictly identical unless Entity 2 is intended to mean Roman slaves. Because Entity 2 is generic and could refer to slaves in any society, they should not be merged as identical. However, if the corpus context indicates both are about Roman society, merging would be appropriate. Given only the provided descriptions, they are related but not strictly the same entity.

'Roman slave' denotes the social category of enslaved people in Roman society, a subset of the broader collective 'Romans' (the Roman people/citizenry). They are related but not identical: one describes a specific social status (slaves) while the other denotes the entire people/society/citizen body. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two refer to different groups: 'Roman slave' denotes the subpopulation of slaves within Roman society, whereas 'Romans' denotes the people/citizen body of Rome as a whole. They are related (slaves were part of Roman society) but not identical entities, different social status and scope.

The two entities are different kinds: one denotes a social class (Roman slaves, people) while the other denotes the Roman state/political entity (Roman Empire). They are related but not identical, so they should not be merged.

The first entity is a social class (slaves in Roman society) while the second is a military organization (the Roman army/legions). They are distinct types and refer to different historical entities though both relate to Rome. They should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct social groups within Roman society: one describes slaves (a subordinate class who could sometimes earn wages or freedom) while the other describes the ruling elite (those who held office and governed). They are related but not the same entity.

Roman religion is a specific aspect/practice within the broader category of Roman culture/civilization. The two are related (religion is part of Roman culture) but are not identical: one denotes the religious practices and institutions, the other denotes the whole civilization including social, artistic, institutional, and material aspects.

Roman religion is a component/aspect of Roman culture/civilization, not the same entity. One is a specific religious system and public practice; the other is the broad civilization encompassing religion, art, institutions, and material culture. They are related but not identical, so they should not be merged.

One is a cultural system/practice (Roman religion), the other is the people/social-political collective (Romans). They are related but not identical — religion is an aspect of Roman society, not the same entity as the Roman people. Therefore they should not be merged.

Greek mythology is the body of myths, gods, and legends originating in ancient Greece. Hellenization is the historical process by which Greek culture (including language, institutions, and elements like religion and mythology) spread to other regions. They are related (Hellenization often involved transmission of Greek myths) but are distinct concepts: one is a cultural tradition, the other is a process of cultural diffusion. Therefore they should not be merged.

Both names refer to the same overall set of classical deities: the Roman collection of gods which overlaps heavily with the Greek pantheon (often syncretized as Graeco-Roman gods). 'Graeco-Roman gods' emphasizes the combined Greek and Roman tradition but denotes the same classical pantheon concept as the 'Roman pantheon' rather than a distinct entity.

The two entries refer to closely related but distinct concepts: one is the corpus of deities and myths (the Graeco-Roman or Roman pantheon), the other is the broader social and public practice of religion in Rome (Roman religion), which includes rituals, cult practice, and state religion beyond just the gods themselves. They are not strictly identical — the pantheon is a component of Roman religion. Therefore they should not be merged.

The first entity is the corpus of deities and religious beliefs (the pantheon), while the second is the broader culture/civilization of ancient Rome (society, institutions, monuments). They are related (religion is part of culture) but are distinct types and referents and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct concepts: one is the corpus of gods and religious beliefs (the Graeco-Roman pantheon), the other is the broader culture/civilization of ancient Rome. They are related (religion is part of culture) but not identical, so they should not be merged.

These are related but distinct cultural/religious groupings. "Egyptian gods" refers specifically to deities of ancient Egyptian religion whose cults sometimes spread into the Roman world. The "Roman (Graeco-Roman) pantheon" refers to the classical Greco-Roman deities and associated religious system. They are not the same single entity but separate pantheons that could interact and syncretize, so they should not be merged.

These refer to different cultural pantheons. "Egyptian gods" denotes deities of ancient Egypt whose cults spread into the Roman world; "Roman (Graeco-Roman) pantheon" denotes the classical Roman/Greek deities and associated religious system. They are related by syncretism and cultural exchange but are not the same single entity, so they should not be merged.
These are two different years (73 BC and 90 BC). They are distinct temporal entities referring to different years and different events (slave revolt vs Social War), so they should not be merged.

These are two different years (temporal entities). They refer to distinct calendar years with different historical events (73 BC: slave revolt; 149 BC: third Punic War start and court creation). They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

The first entity refers generally to the Hellenistic kingdoms (plural)—the successor Hellenistic states after Alexander whose westernizing practices were resisted by Jews. The second entity names the Seleucids (the Seleucid Empire), which is one specific Hellenistic state and not identical to the entire class of Hellenistic kingdoms. They are related (the Seleucids are one of the Hellenistic kingdoms) but not the same entity, so they should not be merged.

Both mentions describe the same concept: regions along the Roman frontier where legions/provincial forces were stationed. 'frontiers' (areas along which legions were distributed) and 'frontier provinces' (regions where the bulk of the legions were stationed) refer to the same set of border provinces/regions under Roman military disposition. They are not distinct entities but two phrasings of the same places.

The two entities are related but not identical. 'Ordinary legionary' refers to individual soldier rank/people serving in the Roman military, whereas 'Roman army' (or 'Roman legions') denotes the overall military organization. They are distinct types (people vs organization) and should not be merged.
